Distinction between instance vs static vs local 

class MyThread implements Runnable {
  int x = 0; // instance field - each new MyThread() gets its OWN copy, not shared
  static int y=0; // static field - ONE copy, shared across all MyThread instances

  public void run() {
    int z=0; // local var - lives on this thread's stack, truly thread local
    x++; // each thread modifies its own x - no race condition, truly thread local
    y++; // all threads modify the same y - race condition
    z++; // only this thread touches z - completely safe
  }

}


Wait-Notify

When we call obj.wait(), current thread gets added to the wait set of that object. 
First it throws the interrupted exception
It does 2 things - it suspends the current execution of the thread and releases the lock

After thread gets suspended due to wait, there has to be a way to wake up the suspended thread.
We can either call obj.notify() or we call interrupt on thread. 

// Thread 1 
synchronized(obj) {
  obj.wait() // this will suspend thread 1's execution, so there has to be a way of waking up this thread
  Sopln()
}

// Thread 2 
synchronized(obj) {
  obj.notify() // notification is perceived at the object level
  Sopln()
}

Important, when thread 2 will call notify, thread 1 does not directly start executing from where it left off because thread2 still has lock on the object.
It just sets the flag that thread 1 can continue execution but thread2 will still need to complete all instructions in its CS. 

obj.notifyAll() will clear the wait set of the object for all threads in the wait set.












